I've successfully bootstrapped a Silex codebase using a small variation of the h2o configuration file for Wordpress that is documented [here](https://github.com/h2o/h2o/wiki/FastCGI-%28Wordpress%29) and [elsewhere](https://www.symfony.fi/entry/serving-php-on-http-2-with-h2o-and-hhvm-symfony-wordpress-drupal).

But there's something that I don't quite like about it: I don't want the flexibility to trigger a FastCGI run for _any_ PHP script, but rather just one or maybe two "whitelisted" scripts. I am struggling to achieve that because the `extension` field of the `file.custom-handler` directive is mandatory.

In essence I'd like some help to translate the minimum, recommended [nginx configuration](http://symfony.com/doc/current/cookbook/configuration/web_server_configuration.html#nginx) for Symfony to an h2o configuration file. An even more succint version could be:

```
server {
    server_name silex.dev;
    root /var/www/silex.dev/web;

    location / {
        try_files $uri /index.php$is_args$args;
    }

    location ~ ^/index\.php(/|$) {
        fastcgi_pass app:9000;

        fastcgi_split_path_info ^(.+\.php)(/.*)$;
        include fastcgi_params;
        fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
        fastcgi_param HTTPS off;

        internal;
    }
}
```

